english:
  title: On Royal Succession
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant makes this memorial:

    In former times, my uncle, the Acting King, served as regent of the kingdom. After my late father, the posthumously honored Grand Tutor, and my uncle the Next in Line passed away one after another, my uncle took up the burden of ruling the domain. Yet disease and misfortune followed in succession. In the sixth lunar month of the fourth year of Qianning, he earnestly pressed upon me the affairs of state, asking me to take them in hand. The officials and common people thrice entreated me to remain, but I steadfastly refused and would not accept the mandate. My uncle then set aside the collective voice, withdrew to his private dwelling.

    I, being unworthy and lacking virtue, have been thrust into this position through error. My spirit trembles as I gaze upon an icy chasm; my shadow shrinks as I look toward the clouded heavens.

    Your servant has heard it said: to advance with difficulty and retreat with ease is the way of the noble man; to serve the public and cast aside the private is what the ancients strived for. Many boast with their lips, yet few practice with their bodies.

    My uncle speaks with urgent passion of establishing virtuous rule and deep reproach of self, saying: "Fire springs from wood, yet fierce fire consumes it; water bears the boat, yet wild water overturns it. Our kingdom now suffers great famine. Bandits rise in every quarter, their greed resembling that of wolves and tigers, their ambitions swelling like wild geese in flight. First they creep as mice, rifling through stores and pouches; then they swarm like hornets, laying waste to cities and plundering villages. Thus smoke and dust fill our borders, winds and rains come unseasonably. Brigands rage in the eastern hills while crops cannot take root in southern fields. The Dragon and Tiger insignia of the Son of Heaven has been swallowed by ravines; the Phoenix envoys from the celestial realm are turned back midway. Our honor is tarnished and our sincere devotion cannot be expressed. Should such failures multiply, the weight of guilt becomes unbearable. Therefore, I have carefully considered the threefold mandate and resolved upon a single act of resignation."

    The officials and nobles of the kingdom gathered in tears, beseeching: "Heaven's calamities are inescapable by earth's division. To blame yourself alone seems unjust. Better to wait for the Emperor's mandate before declining the royal rank."

    Yet when entreaty came more than tenfold and courtesy demanded response beyond the threefold refusal, my uncle spoke to me through tears, saying: "Consider this realm—it differs from other lands. For our kingdom changes its vestments and follows the proper calendar, revering the mandate of the celestial empire while maintaining harmony among the tributary states. Thus the Jade Emperor granted our ancestors verse, saying: 'Propriety and righteousness are first in your kingdom; poetry and books are kept in every home.' And when the imperial envoy Huanghua came and recorded the affairs of Gyerim in verse, he sang: 'Beautiful are the teachings of poetry and books; no trumpet of war disturbs the peace.' Thus the wisdom of ancient worthy rulers shines here. Yet now our districts have become robbers' dens and our mountains are battlefields. Can heaven's calamities fall solely upon our eastern sea? The fault lies in my own ignorance—I have summoned these brigands. My guilt merits death, and in reason I must resign. Therefore, let the kingdom embrace the spirit of yielding; this depends upon two hearts beating as one. Advance this matter and do not follow those who refuse and withdraw."

    Reflecting upon my uncle: he harbors no private ambition, few desires. Loving solitude in his affliction, he speaks only when occasion permits, his resolve unshakeable. If his request for resignation should be refused, he will surely cast off his robes and depart.

    I, though appointed as crown prince through his merit, have received only the benefit of his concern. Song Mu's recommendation of capable virtues differs greatly between life and death; Xie An's service as minister showed care in both beginning and end. Yet my governance of military affairs remains inadequate; the brigands grow ever more troublesome. Though I toil to untangle root and branch, the networks of law continue to spring forth wild. Waters lack boats, roads lack carts—the suffering spreads ever wider.

    Though I cannot journey to the imperial court to lay bare my loyal heart, yet does my spirit drift beyond the Eastern frontier on winds of lingering sorrow, and my sincerity flows toward the celestial capital in tides of pilgrimage.

    Your servant, unworthy in his temporary stewardship of the tributary realm, cannot make swift journey to the imperial presence. Yet how can the heart contain its reverent yearning for imperial grace?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial was composed on behalf of King Hyogong of Silla, as he acceded to the throne.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase 'swan and crane ambitions' (鴻鵠之志) refers to lofty aspirations, alluding to a famous declaration by Chen Sheng during the Qin dynasty's upheaval, when peasants rose in rebellion with grand ambitions.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'Dragon and Tiger insignia' and 'Phoenix envoys' represents imperial authority and diplomatic missions from the Tang court that have been disrupted by civil strife.
